### Security Headers Configuration

Implement headers as middleware to enforce browser security policies. CSP prevents XSS by restricting script sources, HSTS forces HTTPS, X-Frame-Options prevents clickjacking, and X-Content-Type-Options prevents MIME-sniffing. Common mistakes include using 'unsafe-inline' in CSP (defeats the purpose), not setting max-age in HSTS, or using overly permissive policies.

```typescript
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.setHeader('Strict-Transport-Security', 'max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains');
  res.setHeader('X-Content-Type-Options', 'nosniff');
  res.setHeader('X-Frame-Options', 'DENY');
  res.setHeader('Content-Security-Policy', "default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' cdn.example.com");
  res.setHeader('Referrer-Policy', 'strict-origin-when-cross-origin');
  next();
});
```

**Common interview trap:** Setting CSP with 'unsafe-inline' defeats the entire purpose of preventing XSS attacks.

